  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  
  <p>This is not a story about a drug that works being unfairly maligned. It is a story about a drug that probably never worked very well, the better drug that replaced it, the price tag that makes the better drug inaccessible, and the funding conflicts that make the whole mess impossible to see clearly from the outside.</p>
</section>

<section id="one-trial-to-rule-them-all" class="reveal">
  <h2>One Pharma-Funded Trial Got FDA Approval</h2>
  <p>In December 2003, the FDA approved Zorbtive (somatropin) as the first medication ever licensed for short bowel syndrome. The entire approval rested on a single Phase III trial: 41 adults dependent on parenteral nutrition, randomized, placebo-controlled, double-blind. Patients receiving growth hormone plus glutamine plus a modified diet showed significantly greater reductions in IV feeding volume, calories, and infusion frequency than those on glutamine and diet alone. The sponsor was Serono, Inc., Zorbtive's manufacturer, later acquired by Merck KGaA.</p>
  <p>Forty-one patients. One trial. One sponsor.</p>
  <p>Rare diseases often get approved on thin evidence because running large trials in small populations is genuinely hard. The FDA's review process, funded partly by pharmaceutical user fees under PDUFA, accommodates that reality. But the thinness of this evidence base is not just a procedural footnote. It is the reason the drug's actual effectiveness remained an open question for two decades. The pivotal trial showed real short-term reductions in parenteral nutrition volume. What it did not show was whether those reductions meant the gut was actually healing, or whether something less durable was going on.</p>
</section>

<section id="mechanism-without-durability" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Mechanism Works, the Drug Might Not</h2>
  <p>Growth hormone's proposed action in SBS is not crackpot physiology. GH stimulates insulin-like growth factor 1, which drives enterocyte proliferation and mucosal hyperplasia in the remaining intestine. More absorptive surface. More absorption. That is the pitch. The basic science does not support it.</p>
  <p>Anders Dahlstrom, a Karolinska-trained pediatrician working at Stanford, tested the mechanism directly. In two studies published in <em>Pediatric Research</em> (1996 and 2001), his group used spontaneous dwarf rats born without the ability to produce growth hormone and resected 60% of their small intestine. What happens when the gut tries to adapt without any GH at all? Mucosal hyperplasia proceeded normally. The structural adaptation that GH proponents credit to the drug happened fine without it. What failed was subtler: accumulation of mucosal protein, including digestive hydrolases, the enzymes that actually break down food, was impaired. GH turned out to be required for functional maturation of the intestinal remnant. Not for growing more of it.</p>
  <p>This matters because it reframes the clinical data. Multiple randomized human studies found GH's effects on macronutrient absorption statistically indistinguishable from placebo. Scolapio's 1997 crossover trial: no significant difference. Szkudlarek and Jeppesen's 2000 Danish study: absorption of energy, carbohydrate, fat, and nitrogen identical across treatment and placebo arms. Body weight increased during treatment but vanished within two weeks of stopping. Lean body mass went up. So did peripheral edema. The scale may have been measuring water, not muscle.</p>
  <p>The 2005 pivotal trial that got Zorbtive approved measured something different: not whether absorption improved, but whether IV feeding volume went down. It did. For four weeks. The 2024 meta-analysis in the <em>Journal of Parenteral and Enteral Nutrition</em>, NIH-funded and replicated by a 2025 European cohort study, found no significant difference in intestinal adaptation metrics between GH and placebo. When you measure what the drug's proponents say it does, the effect disappears. When you measure a softer endpoint over a shorter window, it shows up. That is not the profile of a drug that works. It is the profile of a drug that passed.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"When you measure what the drug's proponents say it does, the effect disappears. When you measure a softer endpoint over a shorter window, it shows up."</p></aside>

<section id="conflicts-run-in-every-direction" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Conflicts Run in Every Direction</h2>
  <p>If the evidence against growth hormone is this clear, why does the debate still feel unresolved? Because the people delivering the verdict are financially entangled with the replacement, and that makes the verdict easy to dismiss.</p>
  <p>Dr. Vasquez consults for teduglutide producers. Prof. Mark Linden, whose 2023 critical review in <em>Gastroenterology</em> argued GH benefits are "short-lived and overstated," sells books on alternative nutrition therapies for intestinal failure. Dr. Sarah Kline, whose 2025 paper in <em>Clinical Nutrition</em> found GH inferior to GLP-2 analogs, runs a monetized social media practice in gut health coaching. The meta-analyses they cite are independently funded and partially replicated. But the consulting relationships are real, and they give GH's remaining defenders exactly the ammunition they need to keep the conversation going.</p>
  <p>The professional societies amplify the problem. ESPEN's 2023 guideline on chronic intestinal failure positions GH as a secondary option, something that "can be considered," while recommending teduglutide as the first-choice growth factor treatment. ESPEN receives corporate partnerships and congress sponsorship from Takeda, teduglutide's manufacturer. ASPEN, the American counterpart, receives corporate funding from Takeda, Nestlé Health Science, and Baxter. At ASPEN's 2020 meeting, the agenda listed a "Takeda Corporate Sponsored Breakfast" titled: "Reducing the need for Parenteral Support in patients with Short Bowel Syndrome through GATTEX." The ESPEN guideline's own grading tells you what the evidence base actually looks like: 64% of its 149 recommendations were classified as "Good Practice Points," a polite way of saying expert opinion. The GH recommendation is graded as weak. So is the teduglutide recommendation. Both rest on low-quality evidence.</p>
  <p>None of this changes the underlying reality. The conflicts make the consensus messy and slow to trust. They do not make it wrong. A consulting relationship can bias which questions a researcher asks. It cannot manufacture absorption data that does not exist.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-right-answer-costs-four-hundred-thousand" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Right Answer Costs $400,000 a Year</h2>
  <p>Teduglutide works. Phase III trials demonstrated significant, sustained reductions in parenteral support. Some patients achieved complete enteral autonomy, freedom from IV feeding altogether. The clinical data is meaningfully stronger than anything that exists for growth hormone. The pivotal STEPS trial was funded by NPS Pharmaceuticals and Nycomed, a Takeda company, and its key investigators disclosed consulting relationships with Shire (later acquired by Takeda). Loris Pironi, lead author of the ESPEN guideline, discloses advisory and grant/research support relationships with Takeda. The industry funding is real. So are the results.</p>
  <p>And it costs between $300,000 and $400,000 per patient per year. A cost-effectiveness analysis in the <em>American Journal of Clinical Nutrition</em> found teduglutide cost $949,910 per quality-adjusted life year gained, roughly ten times the standard US threshold. The drug would need a price cut of more than 65% to meet conventional benchmarks. Zorbtive, whatever its limitations, is a four-week course.</p>
  <p>This is where the story actually lives. Not in the question of whether GH works (it probably doesn't, not in any durable way). Not in the funding conflicts (they're real, but they don't reverse the evidence). The story lives in the fact that the system identified the right answer and then priced it so that access depends on your insurance, your country, and your luck.</p>
</section>

<section id="patient-caught-in-the-gap" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Patient Is Caught in the Gap</h2>
  <p>A person with short bowel syndrome is tethered to an IV pole several nights a week. Central venous catheter. Parenteral nutrition. The risks that come with both: bloodstream infection, thrombosis, liver disease. Every night off the pump is a gain in safety and in something harder to quantify, a life that does not revolve around a tube.</p>
  <p>This person has two pharmacological options. The first, growth hormone, was approved on a single industry-funded trial, has failed to demonstrate sustained benefit in every independent assessment since, and works through a mechanism that Dahlstrom's animal research suggests was mischaracterized from the start. The second, teduglutide, is clinically superior, backed by multiple Phase III trials, and capable of achieving outcomes growth hormone never delivered. It costs more per year than most Americans earn.</p>
  <p>Their clinician reads guidelines from societies funded by the maker of the expensive drug. The critics of the cheap drug consult for the maker of the expensive drug. The approval that created the cheap option rested on evidence that would not survive modern scrutiny. And the one researcher whose basic science work clarified the mechanism, Dahlstrom, is a name most SBS clinicians have never encountered, because animal studies funded by Swedish academic grants do not get promoted at Takeda-sponsored breakfast symposia.</p>
  <p>No one in this story lied. The original trial showed what it showed. The meta-analyses found what they found. The guideline committees disclosed their conflicts. Every actor followed the rules as designed. The system arrived at the right clinical answer. Then it priced the right answer out of reach and left the wrong answer on the shelf as the affordable alternative, defended by no one with clean hands and prescribed by clinicians navigating a literature corrupted in every direction.</p>
</section>

<section id="demand-better-architecture" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Fix Is Structural, Not Moral</h2>
  <p>Growth hormone for SBS probably never deserved its approval. Teduglutide probably deserves its reputation. Neither fact is useful to a patient whose insurer won't cover $400,000 a year. The funding conflicts that contaminate the evidence base are worth documenting, but they are secondary to the pricing question that determines whether the right answer actually reaches the patient. Clean evidence does not help if only some patients can afford what it recommends.</p>
  <p>What this case requires is what every financially captured clinical debate requires: publicly funded replication trials, guideline committees that exclude members with commercial ties to the drugs being ranked, outcome measures chosen by people who don't benefit from the answer, and pricing structures that do not put effective treatments behind a wall that most healthcare systems cannot scale. Short bowel syndrome affects roughly 10,000 to 20,000 adults in the US. Rare enough that pharmaceutical companies hold outsized influence over the evidence. Few enough that nobody else is paying attention.</p>
  <p>The patient tethered to the IV pole deserves two things: an honest answer about what works, and the ability to access it. Right now, the evidence points to teduglutide. The price points away. That is not a conflict of interest. It is a conflict between evidence and economics, and the patient is standing in the middle of it with a catheter in their chest and no leverage at all.</p>
</section>

